VALUES
(42, 4, 4, 2, 23, 25, 25, 'bread', 'Connection of Sustenance and Service', 'This connection highlights the importance of spiritual sustenance alongside physical needs. Both passages emphasize reliance on God for provision, whether it be ''bread'' or ''every word of God.''', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 4, 49, 6, 17, 17, 'every word of God', 'Connection of God''s Word', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of God''s word in sustaining life and spiritual warfare. Luke highlights living by ''every word of God,'' while Ephesians refers to ''the word of God'' as a weapon.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 4, 42, 4, 10, 10, 'every word of God', 'Connection of Divine Provision', 'Both passages emphasize reliance on God''s word and protection. The first asserts that life is sustained by God''s words, while the second affirms God''s promise of angelic protection, highlighting divine care.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 4, 43, 10, 34, 35, 'every word of God', 'Connection of God''s Word', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the word of God. Luke highlights that man lives by ''every word of God,'' while John asserts that ''the word of God came'' to those called gods, underscoring the authority and power of God''s word.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 5, 62, 2, 15, 16, 'the kingdoms of the world', 'Connection of Worldly Temptation', 'This connection highlights the temptation of worldly power in Luke and the admonition against loving the world in 1 John. Both passages emphasize the allure of worldly desires and the spiritual consequences of succumbing to them.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 5, 18, 20, 5, 5, 'in a moment', 'Triumph of the Wicked', 'Both passages emphasize the fleeting nature of power and joy. In Luke, the devil shows kingdoms ''in a moment,'' while Job notes that the joy of the wicked is ''but for a moment.'' This connection highlights the temporary nature of worldly triumph.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 5, 19, 73, 19, 19, 'in a moment', 'Desolation and Momentary Power', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of suddenness, with Luke highlighting the momentary display of power over kingdoms and Psalms depicting a swift descent into desolation. This connection highlights the transient nature of worldly authority and the terror that can follow.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 5, 40, 4, 8, 8, 'all the kingdoms of the world', 'Connection in Temptation Narrative', 'Both passages emphasize the devil showing Jesus all the kingdoms of the world. The similar phrasing and context indicate a shared narrative focus on temptation and power.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 5, 46, 15, 52, 52, 'in a moment', 'Moment of Transformation', 'This connection highlights the concept of a transformative moment. Both passages emphasize a significant change occurring ''in a moment,'' linking the immediate revelation of kingdoms to the future resurrection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 5, 40, 24, 14, 14, 'kingdoms of the world', 'Connection of Kingdoms and Gospel', 'This connection highlights the theme of kingdoms, as both passages reference the concept of ''kingdoms of the world'' and the ''gospel of the kingdom.'' Both emphasize the significance of the kingdom in relation to the world and its ultimate purpose.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 5, 41, 4, 8, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Growth and Temptation', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the devil''s offer of worldly kingdoms and the fruitful yield of good ground. Both passages emphasize the importance of choices that lead to spiritual growth versus temptation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 6, 43, 12, 31, 31, 'this power will I give thee', 'Authority of the Devil', 'This connection highlights the concept of the ''prince of this world'' and the authority he claims. In Luke, the devil asserts his power, while in John, Jesus speaks of the judgment that leads to the devil''s casting out.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 6, 43, 14, 30, 30, NULL, 'Authority of the Devil', 'This connection highlights the concept of the ''prince of this world'' having authority. In Luke, the devil claims power and glory, while in John, he is identified as the prince who approaches Jesus but finds nothing in Him.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 6, 49, 2, 2, 2, 'power will I give thee', 'Authority of the Devil', 'This connection highlights the theme of the devil''s authority over worldly power. Both passages reference the devil''s role as a ruler, with Luke 4:6 mentioning his claim to power and Ephesians 2:2 identifying him as the ''prince of the power of the air.''', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 6, 62, 5, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Power and Wickedness', 'This connection highlights the theme of power and authority in relation to wickedness. In Luke 4:6, the devil claims power over the world, while 1 John 5:19 states that the whole world lies in wickedness, suggesting a shared understanding of the world''s moral state under such authority.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 6, 66, 13, 2, 2, 'this power will I give thee', 'Authority and Power Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the transfer of power and authority. In Luke, the devil claims he can give power, while in Revelation, the dragon gives power to the beast.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 6, 66, 20, 2, 3, 'the devil said unto him, All this power', 'Connection of Power and Deception', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Devil in relation to power and deception. In Luke, the Devil claims authority over worldly power, while in Revelation, he is bound to prevent his deception of the nations.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 6, 60, 1, 24, 24, 'the glory of them', 'Connection of Glory and Power', 'This connection highlights the transient nature of human glory and power. In Luke, the devil offers power and glory, while 1 Peter emphasizes that all human glory is fleeting, like grass and flowers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 7, 42, 8, 28, 28, 'worship me', 'Worship and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority and worship. In Luke 4:7, the offer of worship is linked to power, while in Luke 8:28, the demoniac recognizes Jesus'' authority as the Son of God, pleading not to be tormented.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 7, 19, 72, 11, 11, 'worship me', 'Worship and Service to Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of worship and service to a higher authority. In Luke, the offer of worship leads to dominion, while in Psalms, the kings and nations serve him, indicating a similar acknowledgment of authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 7, 23, 45, 14, 14, 'all shall be thine', 'Worship and Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and the promise of dominion. In both passages, the idea of receiving power and submission from others is present, emphasizing the authority granted by God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 7, 40, 2, 11, 11, 'worship me', 'Worship and Gifts', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship in both passages. In Luke, the offer to worship leads to the promise of all things, while in Matthew, the act of worship by the Magi is accompanied by the presentation of gifts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 7, 42, 17, 16, 16, 'worship me', 'Worship and Gratitude Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and gratitude. In Luke 4:7, the offer to worship is contrasted with the act of giving thanks in Luke 17:16, where the Samaritan expresses gratitude at Jesus'' feet.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 7, 66, 4, 10, 10, 'worship me, all shall be thine', 'Worship and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and authority. In Luke 4:7, the offer of all things in exchange for worship contrasts with Revelation 4:10, where worship is given to the eternal one, emphasizing rightful worship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 7, 66, 5, 8, 8, 'worship me', 'Worship and Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and its significance in both passages. In Luke 4:7, the offer of worship leads to the promise of dominion, while Revelation 5:8 depicts worship as a response to the Lamb''s authority, emphasizing the importance of worship in recognizing divine sovereignty.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 8, 5, 6, 13, 13, 'Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God', 'Worship and Service to God', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of serving and worshiping the Lord God exclusively. Luke 4:8 directly quotes the command to worship God, paralleling the call to serve Him in Deuteronomy 6:13.', 'theme', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 8, 5, 10, 20, 20, 'him only shalt thou serve', 'Connection of Worship and Service', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of serving God alone. Luke 4:8 quotes Deuteronomy 10:20, reinforcing the theme of exclusive devotion to the Lord.', 'quotation', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 8, 40, 4, 10, 10, 'Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God', 'Connection of Jesus'' Response', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' command to Satan, using the same wording to assert the exclusive worship of God. This connection highlights the consistency in Jesus'' rejection of temptation across the Gospels.', 'parallel', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 8, 19, 83, 18, 18, 'Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God', 'Worship and God''s Sovereignty', 'This connection highlights the theme of worshiping God alone. Both passages emphasize the supremacy of God, with Luke 4:8 affirming exclusive worship and Psalms 83:18 declaring Jehovah as the most high.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 8, 66, 19, 10, 10, 'worship the Lord thy God', 'Worship of God Emphasized', 'Both passages emphasize the exclusive worship of God. In Luke, Jesus asserts that only God should be worshiped, while in Revelation, the angel instructs not to worship him but to worship God instead.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
